content: Hands down the best Pokemon-esque game on mobile. Creos look awesome, the element/evolution system is pretty good though I prefer the standard evolution mechanics that we're used to, I like the addition of healing moves and replacing pp with cooldowns and it doesn't force MTs down your throat. It has a few issues imo though. The ability bar looks old and out of place, only having 5 Creo with you at a time, the map is too small, the game is waaay too easy and it relies on status effects too much.
Frankly, it is average. It is a good clone of pokemon. Catered to nastalgic players. Don't expect more from this game than this. Gameplay is solid.

This review is a long time coming. I was first introduced to EvoCreo on my OUYA. I was looking for a Pokemon-style game and this fit the bill perfectly. I also loved that I could play it on the big screen. Fast forward to today and the game is still wonderful. I am no longer able to play it on the big screen (no Android TV controller support) but the touch controls are easy to use on my phone. That's the 10k foot view from a dad. From my 11yo, she absolutely adores this game. She's a self-proclaimed Pokemon expert and I often find her coming back to EvoCreo as it does a number of things really well. First, the ability to see the strengths and weaknesses of each type simply by tapping on the Creo type while in battle. She finds that super useful. Second, she loves the variety of Creo. Third, the story is good and she feels like there's more to it than simply trying to become a champion. For me, the dad, I'd love to be able to play this on my tv again. It really is a wonderful game and we've enjoyed many many hours of playing it. Keep up the good work Ilmfinity and we're looking forward to EvoCreo 2!

So EvoCreo what can I say about thee? Your microtransactions suck. Your endgame also sucks. The game has a lot of redeeming factors but the combat takes a turn for the worst when you realize 3 status effects can be applied to one Monster. It becomes painfully clear as the monsters begin using nothing but status effect moves to prevent you from battling. EvoCreo needs desperately to remove this and have status effect immunities and limit one per mon. This game should have been sold for 5 dollars without all the bull. However, it has broken combat that becomes a chore only an hour or so in. Sorry EvoCreo, you are literally the worst Pokemon/Digimon substitute. 3/5.

It has only froze on me once. I shut it down. Restarted it and I was literally 2 seconds from where I was. I hadn't saved. So that in it's self is pretty awesome. The game play is decent. Honestly probably as good as you could get for a mobile touch screen device. The story seems pretty well done thus far. I absolutely loved pokemon growing up. I still enjoy it now. While this game may seem like pokemon. In some aspect it is. I would have to say it is it's own entity. The evolution process is interesting. Being as one Creo could actually evolve differently depending on elemental moves used or special gemmas. I was impressed by the fact that this game is easily playable with out spending actual money. I am interested in the expansions however. All in all decent game. I have a S7 and as I said it's only frozen once. I've played over 72 hours. If any one is reading this I would definitely suggest trying it out. It's worth the $1.99

EvoCreo is a marvelous game overall. The story isn't very immersive, so you can progress through the game at your leisure. One may think of this as a budget clone of other games in the Catch 'em RPG genre, but as I myself learned, this is nowhere near the case. The gameplay has a few mechanics that I find delightful. The stacking of Boons and Conditionss to make them last longer and perform better. The move learning, equipping, and using all have a satisfying difficulty, as not learning a move immediately does not mean you can't use it two minutes from now. The additiomal archetypes to regular typing, known as "Class", also put a fun twist on battles, making victory never set in stone just because you dominate the typing game. The only issue I've had is that upon trying to purchase an Alt Creo, the game entered an odd crash state, in which I lost my Prime Gemma and the Alt. I did pay money before hand to get the Gemma, so I was admittedly disappointed. Overall, great story, even if it feels like a prolonged side quest, great gameplay, great Creo, amazing game. Just fix the store please.

Probably one of the most similar games to Pokemon I've ever played without it being one. Mysterious organization. Visiting gyms. One of the functions that feels like a fun upgrade is being able to see which moves your Creo will learn in advance as it allows you to plan evolutions.   One of the new features that isn't so fun is several Creo have like 7 or 8 evolutions, so you have to capture and train the same Creo over and over to get them all. Its not as fun training the same Creo over and over again. So far it seems like 25 Creo are like this, possibly more.  Love the number of 150 Creo. Allows you to feel like you have an achievable goal, rather than some other games that have like 500.

The game is a nice alternative to Pokemon as it was obviously inspired by it. The graphics were nice and the variety of creo was good too. On the other hand DoTs in this game are much too strong, if you don't have at least one poison creo in your party you might as well quit.  Poison by far is the strongest stat, my level 20 creo killed a lvl 83 by just poisoning it then healing.  And since this game gives your creo exponentially more exp if you have a large level difference between you and your opponent I went from like level 20 to 38 in one battle. I also didn't find that elemental matching or opposites to be very functional and you don't seem to need to build a strategic elemental creo team. As long as you have creo that can be immune to each element then you're pretty much set. This game wasn't as grindy or challenging as Pokemon and in most cases the DoTs just made it annoying.

A top-down 2D RPG with tap controls, easy to learn and fun to play! This game is pretty clearly pokemon-dupe, with controls perfectly adapted for mobile devices. There are hundreds of "evocreo" monsters to collect, battle, and evolve, and a lengthy storyline that includes an evil corporation to defeat and battling at gyms to become the best Evo Creo trainer in the world. In-app purchases unlock additional plotlines, but are in no way intrusive or necessary to play and enjoy the game. Fun, low-pressure, and family-friendly, offering dozens of hours of gameplay. Highly recommend!

I played the lite version & truthfully it didn't work all that great on my phone. It heated my phone up a lot. So I figured I would never play the game again or that the full version wasn't worth it.   Anyway I had $1.50 laying on a Visa gift card. I was like blah I am bored & wanted to buy a game. After checking all other 99 cent games I was like blah. Then saw this was 99 cents. I was like nah this is going to be a waste of money if I can't play the lite version what makes the full version better but I was bored & wanted a game to play so I got this.   Went into settings & set it to performance as soon as I got into the main menu. Then to my disbelief I played this game for a whole hour straight without my phone heating up. I was like wow (no really I was lol) so now going to play this game basically 24/7 lol.   Anyway this is a pretty amazing game after getting into it. Not to mention the graphics are great couldn't ask for better lol. I love the fact you can switch out moves that's pretty great not to mention the abilities for your trainer/main character. That's a pretty neat idea actually.   But basically this is Pokemon for your smart phone & love that & truthfully glad I gave the full version a chance. It's a lot more playable then the lite version go figure lol

This game, despite being based off pokemon-is even BETTER than pokemon. The storyline is great with the suspense around every corner and the art style and animation of this game is smooth and well-rounded. However though some of the creo are a bit glitchy and their sprites may be a bit weird. The music is epic and fills you with the feeling that you are actually battleing the person and not just the usual, "ugh a trainer, lets just get this over with". Each creo is unique and the evolution system is just wonky but I like it. Overall, this game is amazeing and I would recommend it to a lot of pokemon fans or people who just love storyline. (Also that Leroy Jenkins reference is pretty sweet.)

Despite what I know you're all thinking, this isn't just a pokemon rip-off. I've played pokemon loyally for as long as I can remember, and I know them as well as anyone. The essence of the game is the same as pokemon, catch the best creatures, train them, beat the town and region champions, etc, but it is balanced MUCH differently. Definitely look through the wiki to see what I mean. It doesn't feel forced or recycled, but is still familiar. The world is beautiful, but I am not thoroughly satisfied with the appearance of the creo themselves, and the world and story are not so large as I had hoped, but still quite sizeable. Also, there is a 'prime gemma' currency mainly used for summoning creo without having to catch them. These can be found in piles, each worth 100, around the world. There are other cons, but mostly minor things that are most likely being worked out as we speak. And if you're uncertain, just get the free version. It's free.

I would highly recommend EvoCreo to any Pokemon fans as it is a great game.

content: Evocreo is one of the best Mon collecting games I've ever played since Cyndaquil and I embarked on my first pokemon adventure in Gold, and certainly the best on Android. It brings plenty of nice ideas to the table, such as the ability to swap out a Creo's move whenever you want, Cool downs on moves rather than power points, moves required for navigation no longer take up move slots, and every Creo having a Healing and Ultimate move. Controls are generally smooth, and they seem to have fixed the D-Pad.

I've loved this game hugely, although I have completed several offers for gemma and never received any, and I am currently unable to progress due to the game controls becoming unresponsive after beating the SH Commander in the lab.   However, I still recommend this game to all my friends; I love that we can trade with each other so easily!

One thing I dont get tho... what's the loyalty bar? What does it do??? I would be over the moon if you actually got back to me on this
replyContent:
Hey S,

Loyalty is... a Creo's loyalty to you. It starts off low when you capture them, but increases as you win with the Creo and keep it in your party, but decreases if you put it in your box or have defeats with it. All it does is effect EXP. The more loyalty you have, the more EXP your Creo will gain.

Hey,

We are working on a fix for that, but use breadcrumbs if you have them to reset you character. If you do not have breadcrumbs then go to menu, then bag, then click on general items 20 times. Exit the bag and re-enter it, and you should have breadcrumbs.

-Ilmfinity Team

I'm gonna be straight with you-- this game has no right to be as absurdly good as it is. Think of it like this; EvoCreo is to Pokemon what Darksiders II is to Zelda. The core gameplay you love is still there, but with interesting, well thought out changes. You may be driven away by the IAPs, but listen-- you flat out never, ever have to spend a cent outside of the primary purchase. There are 3 items that you can get that give you some sort of "advantage:" a (think high IV) basic Creo, level 1. A (high IV) Shiny Creo, level 1. And an item that "de-evolves" Creos to their base form. You caught the evolution you already have, want a different one? This item resets it. That's it. Rest is all visual and doesn't impact gameplay at all.  Game is phenomenal. Easily worth every cent. Online trading. Online battling. Most fun I've had with this type of game since White/Black. My only grievances are as follows: 1.) No renaming of "Creos." Maybe there's a legitimate DB reason for this, but this is a real shame. 2.) No "Shiny" indicator in summary page. 3.) No "You've caught this already" indicator.  Easily recommend to any Pokemon fan, or RPG fan in general.

One of the best games I have played on a mobile device.  The world graphics are great and bring back nostalgia of Pokemon.  The graphics during the battles are wonderful and the Creo animations are superb.  The gameplay mechanics are solid and the touch interface is fantastic during battles.  The ability to "Ride" the Creo and access secret areas is really cool and adds to the gameplay.  Best feature of the game that I wish other games would take note of:  LOCAL SAVE DATA!!!  Yes, you can play this game offline and then upload your save data using Google sign in!  It may seem like a small detail but it is HUGE for me!  I will be making some in-app purchases to support this developer for making such a wonderful game! If you love Pokémon then you will love EvoCreo! The game has the look and feel of the early gameboy advanced titles. The game follows the same general idea of Pokémon catch them all, become the best trainer, and save the region from a nefarious organization. However this game carries many improvements over those gameboy advanced titles. Moves are swappable and you don't need to have your monster forget moves. Your trainer has levels and you can get perks from a talent tree. Your creature also learns abilities which can be used outside of battle and they are also swappable. There is an elemental affinity system which ties into the evolution system. There is tons of neat little enhancements which makes EvoCreo more than just a Pokémon clone.

To move your savefile, first click load->press the orange login button->press the sync button next to the cloud save (This will overwrite and replace the data saved in the cloud with your local save). Now when you go into the full game and login, you will see your saved data.

TLDR: EvoCreo is a flawed, but highly enjoyable experience that I would recommend to any fans of the genre for the asking price.  While clearly pulling many ideas from other sources and even having several cases of Definitely-Not-Pokemon Syndrome, the game also brings several new twists to the formula such as making some "Creo" level up by building up elemental affinity by using moves of that type in battles. Add to this the ability to look up every move a Creo can learn and at what level they learn it in the "Creopedia," and it is very simple to plan out when you want to evolve or wait.  However, there are several notable issues with the game. There are infrequent but noticeable issues with the map and walking through objects or up ledges. Additionally, the "curve" of leveling has multiple spikes and dips which leave you grinding for levels or effortlessly blazing through a section. My last gripe would be with the battle AI, which will spam status moves for no reason, such as spamming critical rate boosting skills after their crit rate is maxed.

This game is a super fun pokemon-inspired rpg with just enough different about it to keep you interested. I'd give it five stars, but there are some (thankfully not game-breaking) bugs. Occasional "null" messages in battle and an inability to open the IAP shop at all are an annoyance, and the ridiculously loud sound effects for some attacks make it impossible to play with the sound on at any level loud enough to hear the music properly. Fun otherwise, though.

The only issue I have noticed is that when I try to leave the game running in the background (to check a notification or anything else), it sometimes starts repeating a screeching noise. I would play with no sound so that this wouldn't matter, but the soundtrack is fantastic. I have to admit that it is a lot like Pokémon, but you can't limit a genre to one game. I think there's plenty of room to say that, with a sequel or two, EvoCreo could be just as good as Pokémon, or even better. Keep up the good work!
